## Stream 1 — Landmark Stream (LRW, Complete)

### Dataset Preparation

A custom scoring pipeline was applied to the full LRW-500 dataset to identify the 100 most linguistically informative words for efficient early experimentation (LRW-100).

**Scoring Formula:**
```
final_score = num_clips × avg_duration × visibility_score × (1 + transition_count)
```

- **Phoneme visibility score**: Assigned per phoneme using CMUdict, averaged across all phonemes in a word
- **Transition count**: Rewards words with distinct, varied mouth movements
- **K-means clustering**: Applied to the scored dataset (features weighted toward phoneme dimensions) to find two naturally forming clusters; 100 words selected from the high-information cluster

### Preprocessing

- **Landmark extractor**: MediaPipe FaceMesh — 40 lip landmarks + 10 chin landmarks = **50 landmarks per frame**
- **Normalisation**: Centered by subtracting mean of all landmarks; scaled by dividing by mouth width (distance between leftmost and rightmost landmarks)
- **Temporal normalisation**: All clips forced to exactly **29 frames** via truncation or zero-padding
- **Output shape**: `(29, 50, 3)` NumPy array per clip

### Experiments Summary

| Exp | Architecture | Dataset | Best Val Acc | Train Acc | Notes |
|-----|-------------|---------|-------------|-----------|-------|
| 01 | ViT (4L, 4H, 256d) — no MLP/BiLSTM | LRW-100 | 61.64% | 74.54% | Spatial landmark set, no flattening |
| 02 | MLP + Temporal Mean Pool | LRW-100 | 4.48% | 5.71% | No temporal direction in mean pool |
| 03 | Deeper MLP + Temporal Mean Pool | LRW-100 | 6.06% | 7.47% | Same pooling failure |
| 04 | MLP + BiLSTM | LRW-100 | 43.96% | 45.97% | Proves sequential modelling is essential |
| 05 | Linear Proj + Transformer + BiLSTM | LRW-100 | 0.82% | — | Linear projection too shallow; early stop |
| 06 | **MLP + Transformer (1L) + BiLSTM** | LRW-100 | **61.58%** | 71.83% | **Primary baseline** |
| 07 | Same as 06 + aggressive augmentation | LRW-100 | 43.20% | 35.08% | Augmentation too aggressive for landmarks |
| 08 | Same as 06 + gentle augmentation | LRW-100 | 54.58% | 55.13% | Landmarks too dense for augmentation |
| 09 | MLP + Transformer (2L) + BiLSTM | LRW-100 | 60.14% | 71.99% | Marginal gain, more overfitting |
| 10 | Same as 09, 80 epochs | LRW-100 | **62.66%** | 78.34% | **Primary ceiling; early stopped ep 54** |
| 11 | MLP + Transformer (3L) + BiLSTM, 80 ep | LRW-100 | 62.66% | 87.18% | Extra layer not justified |
| 12 | 2L Transformer + PE, 50 ep | LRW-100 | 53.08% | 60.27% | PE hurt performance; not converged |
| 13 | Wider MLP + 2L Transformer + BiLSTM | LRW-100 | 60.04% | 89.74% | 16.4M params; same ceiling, worse overfit |
| 14 | Same as 13, dropout 0.4 | LRW-100 | 59.92% | 97.42% | Overfitting widened |
| 15 | Warm start from exp 10 → 500 words | LRW-500 | 42.95% | 67.60% | Warm start from 100-word model hurts |
| 16 | Same as 15, increased dropout | LRW-500 | 41.86% | 56.57% | Healthier train/val gap |
| 17 | Confusion matrix analysis (exp 10) | LRW-100 | — | — | Bottom-20 words identified |
| 18 | Full scratch training, 80 ep | LRW-500 | 41.78% | 62.58% | ~110 words near-zero acc; hard vocab limit |

### Key Findings — Landmark Stream

- **62.66% appears to be a robust ceiling** across radically different architectures (ViT spatial at 61.64% vs flattened MLP+Transformer at 62.66%), suggesting the ceiling is a **property of the features**, not the architecture
- **Sequential modelling is essential**: mean pooling achieves <7%; BiLSTM brings this to 44% (Exp 04)
- **Landmarks are too semantically dense for augmentation**: geometric perturbations destroy the signal rather than regularising
- **Hard vocabulary limit at LRW-500**: ~110 short, visually ambiguous words (e.g. *about*, *across*, *action*) achieve near-zero accuracy — these represent a fundamental limit of what geometric features can distinguish

